<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-285-516  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 285 516.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  May 15 1989 v15 n10 p28(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>What's right with America's IC equipment makers? ( includesrelated articles on materials in Japan, purchasing equipment inthe IC industry, and market opportunities in South Korea)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rice, Valerie.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>US semiconductor equipment makers have lost world leadership toJapan and they may not be able to win it back.andP;  The US share ofthe worldwide market fell from 62 percent in 1982 to 45 percent in1987 while the Japanese share rose from 29 percent to 44 percent,mostly in wafer steppers.andP;  The market grew from $1.4 billion to$3.1 billion in that time.andP;  Fortunes of the equipment makers arebound up with those of their customers, the semiconductormanufacturers, who are also losing market share.andP;  The most obviousproblem with the production equipment industry is structural.andO;Eight hundred US companies, averaging sales of $7 million peryear, are competing at a time when purchasers are turning tolarger, more stable companies.andP;  Another problem is that USequipment makers tend to focus on short-term profits, resulting inpoor quality.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Integrated circuitsMarket ShareJapanese CompetitionInternational TradeMarketing StrategyGoals and ObjectivesIndustry AnalysisOutlookSemiconductor Production Equipment.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphphotographtable.andO;Caption:   U.S. suppliers' downhill slide. (graph)Reliability of U.S. IC equipment. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>